The '''Escrit√≥rio Central de Arrecada√ß√£o e Distribui√ß√£o''' (also known as '''ECAD'''; can be translated as ''Central Bureau for Collection and Distribution''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ecad.org.br/en/about-us/the-ecad/Pages/default.aspx|title=Ecad Direitos Autorais :: Ecad|last=|first=|date=|website=ecad.org.br|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=18 July 2018}}</ref>) is the national copyright collection agency in [[Brazil]]. It is made up of six partner organisations:  BRAMUS, AMAR, SBACEM, SICAM, SOCINPRO and UBC, as well as associate member organisations ABRAC, ANACIM, ASSIM and SADEMBR.<ref>[http://prsformusic.com/creators/news/research/Documents/Page,%20Gandelman,%20Dickinson%20%282010%29%20ECADonomics.pdf ECADonomics], PRS for Musi</ref><ref name="BassoJunior2010">{{cite book|author1=Maristela Basso|author2=Edson Beas Rodrigues Junior|title=Intellectual Property Law in Brazil|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HmuoES8K5tAC&pg=PA43|year=2010|publisher=Kluwer Law International|isbn=978-90-411-3378-6|pages=42‚Äì43}}</ref>

ECAD also produce a Radio Ranking of music based on radio airplay.<ref>http://www.ecad.org.br/pt/eu-faco-musica/Ranking/SitePages/ranking.aspx</ref>

== Controversies ==
In 2012, fifteen officials were indicted after an investigation by the Brazilian Senate found that some at ECAD had allegedly taken money intended for artists and had engaged in price fixing.<ref name="Ars">[https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2012/05/copyright-cops-behaving-badly/ Not just the pirates: Brazilian rights holders indicted for ripping off artists], Ars Technica</ref>

[[Ronaldo Lemos]], an academic from [[Funda√ß√£o Get√∫lio Vargas]], has said he believes ECAD used legal pressure on their critics and described them as a "litigation machine". Lemos claimed that leaked documents from ECAD showed that they planned to sue him.<ref name="Ars" />

